Choosing a K Value¶

In [20]:
# creates a for loop to train various KNN models with different k values and stores the error_rate for the models

error_rate  = []

for i in range(1,40):
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=i)
    knn.fit(X_train, y_train)
    pred_i = knn.predict(X_test)
    error_rate.append(np.mean(pred_i != y_test))
In [23]:
# plots the error rate vs. k values to see the lowest error rates for each k value in the range (0-40)

plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
plt.plot(range(1,40), error_rate, color='black', alpha=0.8, linestyle='--', marker='o',
        markerfacecolor='g', markersize=10)
plt.title('Error Rate vs K Value')
plt.xlabel('K')
plt.ylabel('Error Rate');

Retrain with new K Value¶

In [22]:
# retrains model with the new k value of 38, giving the highest accuracy score to the model

knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=38)
knn.fit(X_train, y_train)
pred = knn.predict(X_test)

print(confusion_matrix(y_test, pred))
print('\n')
print(classification_report(y_test, pred))
